{"title_page": "Colonial charters in the Thirteen Colonies", "text_new": "A '''charter''' is a [[document]] that gave colonies the [[Droit de r\u00e9gale|legal rights]] to exist. Charters can bestow certain rights on a [[town]], [[city]], [[university]] or an institution.\n\nColonial Charters were empowered when the king gave a grant of exclusive powers for the governance of land to proprietors or a settlement company. The charters defined the relationship of the colony to the mother country, free from involvement from the Crown. For the trading companies, charters vested the powers of government in the company in England. The officers would determine the administration, laws, and ordinances for the colony, but only as conforming to the laws of England. [[Proprietary colony|Proprietary charters]] gave governing authority to the proprietor, who determined the form of government, chose the officers, and made laws, subject to the advice and consent of the freemen. All colonial charters guaranteed to the colonists the vague [[rights of Englishmen|rights and privileges of Englishmen]], which would later cause trouble during the revolutionary era. In the second half of the seventeenth century, the Crown looked upon charters as obstacles to colonial control, substituting the royal province for corporations and proprietary governments.\n\n==History==\nThe Virginia and Massachusetts charters were given to business corporations. Regular meetings of company officers and stockholders were the only governmental institutions required. The Virginia charter, [[Charter of 1606|issued in 1606]], and [[Second Virginia Charter|revised in 1609]] and 1612, was revoked upon bankruptcy of the sponsoring and organizing [[Virginia Company of London]] in 1624. The second Colonial Charter was granted to [[Colony of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts Bay]] in 1629, settling at [[Boston]] and [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], a decade after the first \"New Englanders\" at [[Plymouth Colony]] further south towards [[Cape Cod]]. In 1684, the Chancery Court in England voided the charter and changed it to a royal colony. [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] placed Massachusetts under the authority of the unified [[Dominion of New England]] in 1685. After [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary II]] had ascended to the thrones of England, Scotland and Ireland, in addition to the stewardship of the Dutch Republic, they issued Massachusetts Bay a new liberal charter in 1691.\n\nCharles II granted Connecticut its charter in 1662 with the right of self-government. When [[James II of England|James II]] ascended the throne in 1685, he tried to revoke the Connecticut charter and sent  [[Edmund Andros|Sir Edmund Andros]] to receive it for the Crown. [[Joseph Wadsworth|Captain Joseph Wadsworth]] spirited the precious document out a window and stole the charter and hid it in a hollow oak tree, the \"[[Charter Oak incident|Charter Oak]],\" until James was overthrown. Connecticut temporarily lost the right of self-government under the unification of the several colonies into the [[Dominion of New England]] in 1687, but it was reinstated in 1689. The last charter by Charles II was issued to Rhode Island in 1663. [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]] and [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations|Rhode Island]] attained colonial charters as already established colonies that allowed them to elect their own governors.\n\nAs a result of political upheavals, especially after the three [[English Civil War]]s in the 1640s, and the later \"[[Glorious Revolution]]\" of 1688 with their [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]--[[Church of England|Protestant/Anglican]] conflicts which also transformed into struggles between the [[King of England|King]] and [[English Parliament|Parliament]]. As these conflicts traveled across the [[Atlantic Ocean]], most colonies eventually surrendered their charters to the Crown by 1763 and became royal colonies as the King and his Ministers asserted more centralized control of their previously neglected and autonomous [[Thirteen Colonies]]. By the late 1600s, the colonial [[Province of Maryland|Maryland]], had its Proprietary Charter to the [[Lords Baltimore]] revoked and had become a royal colony with its [[Governor of Maryland]] appointed by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Monarch]] with the advice of his Ministers and the Colonial Offices and Board of Trade of members from [[British Parliament|Parliament]].\n\nBy 1776, when the [[Province of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] and its lower [[History of Delaware|Delaware Bay counties]] remained proprietary colonies under a charter originally granted to [[William Penn]] and his heirs. The [[Province of Connecticut]] and the [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations|Province of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]] continued as corporation colonies under charters, and [[History of Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] was governed as a royal province while operating under a charter after the unifying of the older \"Massachusetts Bay\" colony at [[History of Boston|Boston]] and the \"first landing\" colony, [[Plymouth Colony]] at [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]], with its famous \"[[Mayflower Compact]]\" from 1620. Further south, the [[Province of Virginia|Provinces of Virginia]], [[Province of North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[Province of South Carolina|South Carolina]], and [[Province of Georgia|Georgia]] to the undefined border with [[Spanish Florida]], all had their original charters dismissed with different opinions about the role and powers and taxing authority between the Royal Governors and their increasingly restless and defiant colonial Assemblies. The Royal Authority reasserted itself and becoming governed more directly from [[London]] with increasing friction as the 18th Century progressed to its [[American Revolutionary War|revolutionary]] climax.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Colonial government in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n*[[Colonial history of the United States]]\n*[[Proprietary colony]]\n*[[State constitution (United States)]]\n\n==References==\n* [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/subject_menus/statech.asp The Avalon Project: Colonial Charters, Grants, and Related Documents] Bibliography\n* Bridenbaugh, Carl. Early Americans. New York: Oxford University Press, 1981.\n* Ernst, Joseph Albert. The Forming of a Nation, 1607\u20131781. New York: Random House, 1970.\n* Middleton, Richard. Colonial America: A History, 1585\u20131776. Cambridge, Mass.: Blackwell, 1996.\n* Ubbelohde, Carl. The American Colonies and the British Empire, 1607\u20131763. New York: Crowell, 1968.\n* Kemp, Roger L., \"Model Government Charters: A City, County, Regional, State, and Federal Handbook,\" McFarland and Co., Inc.,Publsiher. Jefferson, NC, and London, ENG (2007).  (ISBN: 978-0-7864-3154-0).\n* Kemp, Roger L., \"Documents of Democracy: A Collection of Essential Works,\" McFarland and Co., Inc., Publsiher, Jefferson, NC, and London, ENG (2010). (ISBN: 978-0-7864-4210-2).\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.answers.com/topic/colonial-charter#ixzz1BJJylbAG  Colonial Charters] at [[Answers.com]]\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/federalstatecons01thor/ |title=The Federal and State Constitutions, Colonial Charters, and Other Organic Laws of the State, Territories, and Colonies |last=Thorpe |first=Francis Newton |year=1909 |volume=I-VII |website=Internet Archive |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |oclc=958714228}}\n\n\n[[Category:Political charters]]\n[[Category:Colonial government in America]]\n[[Category:Governance of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Thirteen Colonies documents]]\n[[Category:English law]]\n", "text_old": "A '''charter''' is a [[document]] that gave colonies the [[Droit de r\u00e9gale|legal rights]] to exist. Charters can bestow certain rights on a [[town]], [[city]], [[university]] or an institution.\n\nColonial Charters were empowered when the king gave a grant of exclusive powers for the governance of land to proprietors or a settlement company. The charters defined the relationship of the colony to the mother country, free from involvement from the Crown. For the trading companies, charters vested the powers of government in the company in England. The officers would determine the administration, laws, and ordinances for the colony, but only as conforming to the laws of England. [[Proprietary colony|Proprietary charters]] gave governing authority to the proprietor, who determined the form of government, chose the officers, and made laws, subject to the advice and consent of the freemen. All colonial charters guaranteed to the colonists the vague [[rights of Englishmen|rights and privileges of Englishmen]], which would later cause trouble during the revolutionary era. In the second half of the seventeenth century, the Crown looked upon charters as obstacles to colonial control, substituting the royal province for corporations and proprietary governments.\n\n==History==\nThe Virginia and Massachusetts charters were given to business corporations. Regular meetings of company officers and stockholders were the only governmental institutions required. The Virginia charter, [[Charter of 1606|issued in 1606]], and [[Second Virginia Charter|revised in 1609]] and 1612, was revoked upon bankruptcy of the sponsoring and organizing [[Virginia Company of London]] in 1624. The second Colonial Charter was granted to [[Colony of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts Bay]] in 1629, settling at [[Boston]] and [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], a decade after the first \"New Englanders\" at [[Plymouth Colony]] further south towards [[Cape Cod]]. In 1684, the Chancery Court in England voided the charter and changed it to a royal colony. [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] placed Massachusetts under the authority of the unified [[Dominion of New England]] in 1685. After [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary II]] had ascended to the thrones of England, Scotland and Ireland, in addition to the stewardship of the Dutch Republic, they issued Massachusetts Bay a new liberal charter in 1691.\n\nCharles II granted Connecticut its charter in 1662 with the right of self-government. When [[James II of England|James II]] ascended the throne in 1685, he tried to revoke the Connecticut charter and sent  [[Edmund Andros|Sir Edmund Andros]] to receive it for the Crown. [[Joseph Wadsworth|Captain Joseph Wadsworth]] spirited the precious document out a window and stole the charter and hid it in a hollow oak tree, the \"[[Charter Oak incident|Charter Oak]],\" until James was overthrown. Connecticut temporarily lost the right of self-government under the unification of the several colonies into the [[Dominion of New England]] in 1687, but it was reinstated in 1689. The last charter by Charles II was issued to Rhode Island in 1663. [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]] and [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations|Rhode Island]] attained colonial charters as already established colonies that allowed them to elect their own governors.\n\nAs a result of political upheavals, especially after the three [[English Civil War]]s in the 1640s, and the later \"[[Glorious Revolution]]\" of 1688 with their [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]--[[Church of England|Protestant/Anglican]] conflicts which also transformed into struggles between the [[King of England|King]] and [[English Parliament|Parliament]]. As these conflicts traveled across the [[Atlantic Ocean]], most colonies eventually surrendered their charters to the Crown by 1763 and became royal colonies as the King and his Ministers asserted more centralized control of their previously neglected and autonomous [[Thirteen Colonies]]. By the late 1600s, the colonial [[Province of Maryland|Maryland]], had its Proprietary Charter to the [[Lords Baltimore]] revoked and had become a royal colony with its [[Governor of Maryland]] appointed by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Monarch]] with the advice of his Ministers and the Colonial Offices and Board of Trade of members from [[British Parliament|Parliament]].\n\nBy 1776, when the [[Province of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] and its lower [[History of Delaware|Delaware Bay counties]] remained proprietary colonies under a charter originally granted to [[William Penn]] and his heirs. The [[Province of Connecticut]] and the [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations|Province of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]] continued as corporation colonies under charters, and [[History of Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] was governed as a royal province while operating under a charter after the unifying of the older \"Massachusetts Bay\" colony at [[History of Boston|Boston]] and the \"first landing\" colony, [[Plymouth Colony]] at [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]], with its famous \"[[Mayflower Compact]]\" from 1620. Further south, the [[Province of Virginia|Provinces of Virginia]], [[Province of North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[Province of South Carolina|South Carolina]], and [[Province of Georgia|Georgia]] to the undefined border with [[Spanish Florida]], all had their original charters dismissed with different opinions about the role and powers and taxing authority between the Royal Governors and their increasingly restless and defiant colonial Assemblies. The Royal Authority reasserted itself and becoming governed more directly from [[London]] with increasing friction as the 18th Century progressed to its [[American Revolutionary War|revolutionary]] climax.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Colonial government in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n*[[Colonial history of the United States]]\n*[[Proprietary colony]]\n*[[State constitution (United States)]]\n\n==References==\n* [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/subject_menus/statech.asp The Avalon Project: Colonial Charters, Grants, and Related Documents] Bibliography\n* Bridenbaugh, Carl. Early Americans. New York: Oxford University Press, 1981.\n* Ernst, Joseph Albert. The Forming of a Nation, 1607\u20131781. New York: Random House, 1970.\n* Middleton, Richard. Colonial America: A History, 1585\u20131776. Cambridge, Mass.: Blackwell, 1996.\n* Ubbelohde, Carl. The American Colonies and the British Empire, 1607\u20131763. New York: Crowell, 1968.\n* Kemp, Roger L., \"Model Government Charters: A City, County, Regional, State, and Federal Handbook,\" McFarland and Co., Inc.,Publsiher. Jefferson, NC, and London, ENG (2007).  (ISBN: 978-0-7864-3154-0).\n* Kemp, Roger L., \"Documents of Democracy: A Collection of Essential Works,\" McFarland and Co., Inc., Publsiher, Jefferson, NC, and London, ENG (2010). (ISBN: 978-0-7864-4210-2).\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.answers.com/topic/colonial-charter#ixzz1BJJylbAG  Colonial Charters] at [[Answers.com]]\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/federalstatecons01thor/ |title=The Federal and State Constitutions, Colonial Charters, and Other Organic Laws of the State, Territories, and Colonies |last=Thorpe |first=Francis Newton |year=1909 |volume=I-VII |website=Internet Archive |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |oclc=630322887}}\n\n\n[[Category:Political charters]]\n[[Category:Colonial government in America]]\n[[Category:Governance of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Thirteen Colonies documents]]\n[[Category:English law]]\n", "name_user": "Jphill19", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Template Correction ~ OCLC No.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colonial_charters_in_the_Thirteen_Colonies"}
{"title_page": "Yura (South Korean singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean singer}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Yura\n| image           = Yura - 2016 Gaon Chart K-pop Awards red carpet 03.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| caption         = Yura on the red carpet of the Gaon Chart K-pop Awards, on February 17, 2016.\n| native_name     = \uae40\uc544\uc601\n| birth_name      = Kim Ah-young\n| alias           = Yura\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1992|11|6}}\n| birth_place     = [[Ulsan]], South Korea\n| education       = [[Dongduk Women's University]]\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|actress}}\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = [[K-pop]]\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| years_active    = 2010\u2013present\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dream T Entertainment|Dream T]]|Awesome Ent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3061203|title=Girl's Day members pivot to acting|date=March 30, 2019|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>}}\n| associated_acts = [[Girl's Day]]\n}}}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = {{linktext|\uae40|\uc544\uc601}}\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u4e9e|\u7469}}\n| rr              = Gim A-yeong\n| mr              = Kim Ay\u014fng\n| hangulstage     = {{linktext|\uc720|\ub77c}}\n| hanjastage      = {{linktext|\u5ba5|\u62c9}}\n| rrstage         = Yu-ra\n| mrstage         = Yura\n}}\n\n'''Kim Ah-young''' (born November 6, 1992),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%9C%A0%EB%9D%BC&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=189556|title=\uc720\ub77c \ud504\ub85c\ud544|work=Naver|language=ko}}</ref> better known by her stage name '''Yura''', is a South Korean singer and actress. She is best known as a member of the South Korean [[girl group]] [[Girl's Day]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nYura was born on November 6, 1992 in [[Ulsan]], South Korea.<ref name=mk /> She attended Ulsan Art High School as a dance major. Yura is currently attending [[Dongduk Women's University]], alongside fellow group member [[Bang Min-ah|Minah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2011&no=75199|title= \uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, \ub3d9\ub355\uc5ec\ub300 \ubc29\uc1a1\uc5f0\uc608\uacfc \uc9c4\ud559 '2011\ub144 \uc0c8\ub0b4\uae30 |work=MK News|date=February 5, 2011|language=ko}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===2010: Girl's Day===\nIn 2010, Yura became a member of the K-pop girl group [[Girl's Day]], where she and [[Lee Hye-ri]] replaced two of the former members, Ji-in and Ji-sun, who left after having been with the group for two months.<ref name=mk>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/40220|title=[Interview] My Name Is\u2026 Girl's Day \u2013 Part. 1|date=December 9, 2012|work=TenAsia}}</ref> Dream Tea promoted Girl's Day before their debut with the creation of an official Fan Caf\u00e9, a YouTube channel, and Twitter accounts for the group and each of its members. The group also conducted a flash mob dance before the debut in the commercial and entertainment districts of [[Seoul]], gaining much interest.\n\n===2012\u20132014: Acting debut and collaborations===\nIn 2012, Yura made her acting debut through [[Sohu|Sohu TV]]'s Chinese drama ''Secret Angel''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/10159|title=Girl's Day Yura joins Jang Woo-hyuk in Chinese drama \"Secret Angel\"|date=March 7, 2012|work=TenAsia}}</ref> She then collaborated with her label-mate Jevice with their single \"I'll Love You\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} Yura also featured in [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]'s series ''[[To the Beautiful You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2012080910312231627&type=3|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\uc544\uadf8\ub300' \uce90\uc2a4\ud305..\uc774\ubbfc\ud638 \uc5f4\ud608\ud32c \uc5ed|date=August 9, 2012|work=Star News|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Yura was cast in the sitcom ''Reckless Family 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/66199|title=Girl's Day Yura Cast in Sitcom|date=July 24, 2013|work=10Asia}}</ref> She also featured in a special episode of KBS' night show ''The Clinic for Married Couples: Love and War 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/68096|title=ZE:A Moon Jun-young to Pair Up with Girl's Day Yura in TV Show|date=August 7, 2013|work=TenAsia}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, Yura starred in the SBS mini drama ''Be Arrogant''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/news_detail.asp?mediaCodeNo=258&newsId=01243126606255216|title='\ub3c4\ub3c4\ud558\ub77c' \uc720\ub77c\u00b7\uc2e0\uc18c\uc728, '2014 \ub2e8\ub9c9\uadf9 \ud398\uc2a4\ud2f0\ubc8c' \ud3ec\ubb38 \uc5f0\ub2e4|date=October 21, 2014|work=E Daily|language=ko}}</ref> She then became one of the official couples for the variety show ''[[We Got Married]]'', where she was paired with model-actor [[Hong Jong-hyun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.asiatoday.co.kr/view.php?key=20140529001128565|title=Model-actor Hong Jong-hyun and Girl's Day Yura join 'We Got Married'|date=May 29, 2014|work=Asia Today}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: MC and acting===\nIn 2015, Yura co-hosted the [[K-pop Star 4|fourth season]] of reality competition series ''[[K-pop Star]]'' alongside [[Jun Hyun-moo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003015182|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, 'K\ud31d\uc2a4\ud0c04' \uc0dd\ubc29\uc1a1 MC \ud569\ub958..\uc804\ud604\ubb34\uc640 \ud638\ud761|date=March 12, 2015|work=Osen|language=ko}}</ref> Additionally, Yura also serves as the MC for joint Korean-Chinese audition program ''Super Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000493065|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\uc288\ud37c\uc544\uc774\ub3cc' MC \ub099\uc810\u2026\uc870\ub825\uc790 \uc5ed\ud560|date=July 9, 2015|work=Xports News|language=ko}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2016, Yura was cast as one of the new MCs of Olive Channel's ''Tasty Road'' with [[Kim Min-jung (actress)|Kim Min-jung]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1110336196|title=\uae40\ubbfc\uc815\u00b7\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ud14c\uc774\uc2a4\ud2f0 \ub85c\ub4dc' MC \ud655\uc815|date=January 19, 2016|work=Osen|language=ko}}</ref> The same year, she joined tvN's variety show ''After the Play Ends'' and acted in the web drama ''Iron Lady''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=14672438801131175019|title='\uc5f0\uadf9\uc774 \ub05d\ub098\uace0 \ub09c \ub4a4' \ud558\uc11d\uc9c4\u00b7\uc724\uc18c\ud76c\u00b7\uc774\ubbfc\ud601\u00b7\uc720\ub77c, \uc0dd\uc0dd\ud55c \ud604\uc7a5\ucef7|date=June 30, 2016|work=TV Daily|language=ko}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Yura was cast as one of the new MCs of [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]'s ''Life Bar'' with [[Kim Hee-chul]], joining original MCs [[Shin Dong-yup (comedian)|Shin Dong-yup]] and [[Kim Jun-hyun (comedian)|Kim Jun-hyun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201704191651001775141_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Super Junior's Kim Hee-chul, Girl's Day's Yura to host 'Life Bar'|date=April 19, 2017|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> She was also chosen as one of the MCs for KBS Drama's ''Beauty Bible 2017'', alongside [[Han Hye-jin]]  and [[Im Soo-hyang]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0002908809|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ubdf0\ud2f0 \ubc14\uc774\ube14 2017' MC \ubc1c\ud0c1..\u65b0 \ubdf0\ud2f0\uc5ec\uc2e0|work=Herald Corporation|language=ko|date=April 6, 2017|accessdate=2017-06-12}}</ref> The same year, she starred in JTBC's short drama ''Hip Hop Teacher''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=117&aid=0002901082|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] \uc218\uc601\u00b7\uc774\uc6d0\uadfc\ubd80\ud130 \uc720\ub77c\u00b7\ub2c9\ucfe4\uae4c\uc9c0\u2026JTBC, \uc6f9\ub4dc \ub77c\uc778\uc5c5 \uacf5\uac1c|work=My Daily|language=ko|date=April 20, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Yura starred in KBS' romance drama ''[[Radio Romance (TV series)|Radio Romance]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kbsworld.kbs.co.kr/news/news_view.php?no=18016|title=Girl's Day Yura to star in 'Radio Romance' with Kim So Hyun & Yoon Doo Joon|website=KBS World|publisher=KBS World|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201804011415228184249_2|title=Yura in love with sweet villain character|date=April 1, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Lawsuit===\nOn November 8, 2010, Yura's ex-management company Action Music Entertainment filed an injunction against Yura, stopping her from signing a second contract with Dream Tea Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/11/08/2010110801660.html|title='\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774' \uc720\ub77c, \uc5f0\uc608\ud65c\ub3d9 \uae08\uc9c0 \uac00\ucc98\ubd84 \uc18c\uc1a1 \ub2f9\ud574|date=November 8, 2010|work=Chosun|language=ko}}</ref> In response, representatives of Dream Tea stated Action Music had violated contractual terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010110813305072713|title='\uc18c\uc1a1' \uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uce21 \"\uc720\ub77c, \uc544\ubb34 \ubb38\uc81c \uc5c6\uc774 \uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \uc774\uc801\"|date=November 11, 2010|work=Asiae|language=ko}}</ref> The lawsuit was pursued when Action Music insisted that they had a video of Yura's unacceptable behavior. On January 20, 2011, the court ruled in Yura's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.segye.com/newsView/20110128001761|title='\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774' \uc720\ub77c, \u524d\uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \ubd84\uc7c1\uc5d0\uc11c \uc774\uacbc\ub2e4|work=Segye|date=January 28, 2011|language=ko}}</ref> \n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Girl's Day discography}}\n\n===As featured artist===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Title\n! rowspan=2 | Year\n! colspan=\"1\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=2 | Sales\n! rowspan=2 | Album\n|-\n! style=\"font-size:90%;\"| [[Gaon Digital Chart|KOR<br>Gaon]]\n|-\n| \"I'll Love You\" <br>{{small|(Jevice featuring Yura of [[Girl's Day]])}}<br> || 2012 || \u2014 || \u2014 || {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010 || ''I Trusted Him'' || || [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] || Cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2012 || ''The Secret Angel'' || Yu-bin || [[Sohu|Sohu TV]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[To the Beautiful You]]'' || Lee Eun-young || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n| ''Reckless Family 3'' || Park Yoo-ra || [[MBC Every 1]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Family (2012 TV series)|Family]]'' ||  || rowspan=2|[[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS2]] || Cameo, Episode 11<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kwon|first1=Hye-rim|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ubb34\uc791\uc815\ud328\ubc00\ub9ac3' \uce90\uc2a4\ud305|trans-title=Girl's Day Yura Cast in 'Recklessly family 3'|url=http://joynews.inews24.com/php/news_view.php?g_menu=700200&g_serial=759665&rrf=nv|website=Joy News|accessdate=2013-08-03|date=July 17, 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n| ''The Clinic for Married Couples: Love and War 2'' || Yoo-jung || \n|-\n| 2014 || ''Be Arrogant'' || Hong Ha-ra || [[SBS Plus]] ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Iron Lady'' || Jenny || [[tvN]] ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''Hip Hop Teacher'' || Kim Yoo-bin || [[JTBC]] ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Radio Romance (TV series)|Radio Romance]]'' || Jin Tae-ri || [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS2]] ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Psychopath Diary|Psychopath Diary]]'' || || [[tvN]] || Cameo, Episode 2 \n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Find Me in Your Memory]]'' || Go Yu-ra || [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] || Cameo, Episodes 2 & 4\n|}\n\n===Variety show===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''We Are Dating''\n| rowspan=2|MBC\n| \n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[We Got Married]]'' \n| with [[Hong Jong-hyun]] (Episodes 91\u2013131) \n|-\n|2015\n| ''[[Off to School]]''||  JTBC|| Episodes 40\u201343<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/495719|title='\ud559\uad50 \ub2e4\ub140\uc624\uaca0\uc2b5\ub2c8\ub2e4' \uc740\uc9c0\uc6d0 \uc720\ub77c \uc2ac\uae30, \ub9cc\ud654\ucc3d\uc791\uacfc \uc804\ud559\uc0dd\uc73c\ub85c \ud569\ub958|date=April 14, 2015|work=TenAsia|language=ko}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2016\n|''After The Play Ends''\n|tvN \n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Living Together in Empty Room]]'' || MBC || Episodes 4\u20138<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?2998631|title='\ubc1c\uce59\ud55c\ub3d9\uac70'\uc720\ub77cX\uae40\ubbfc\uc885X\uae40\uad6c\ub77c, \ub098\uc774\ucc28\uc774 \ubb34\uc0c9\ud55c '\ub3d9\uc2ec \ub77c\uc774\ud504'(\uc885\ud569)|work=News1 Korea|language=ko|date=May 19, 2017|accessdate=2017-06-12|last=Lee|first=Hyun-ju}}</ref><br/>Episodes 19\u201321<ref>{{Cite news|author=Lee Eun-jin|title='\ubc1c\uce59\ud55c \ub3d9\uac70' \uae40\ubbfc\uc885X\uc18c\uc9c4, \uc720\ub77c \uc9d1\uc5d0\uc11c \ub2e4\uc2dc \ub3d9\uac70 \uc2dc\uc791\u2026 '\ubc18\uac00\uc6b4 \uc7ac\ud68c'|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1279138|work=TenAsia|date=August 24, 2017|accessdate=2017-08-25|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n|''Ocean Police''\n| MBC Every1\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/yura-to-star-in-tv-show-ocean-police-with-kim-soo-ro-jo-jae-yoon-and-kwak-si-yang-120529.html|title=Yura to Star in TV Show \"Ocean Police\" With Kim Soo-ro, Jo Jae-yoon and Kwak Si-yang|date=July 19, 2018|website=Hancinema|publisher=Star News|language=}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Those Who Cross the Line]]''\n| MBC\n| Episodes 17-20\n|-\n|2018\n|''Give & Take, Please Buy'' || MBN || \n|- \n|2019\n|''Cabin Crew'' || [[Channel A (TV channel)|Channel A]] || Episodes 1\u201312\n|- \n|2019\n|''[[Seoul Mate|Seoul Mate 3]]''\n|[[TVN (South Korean TV channel)|tvN]]\n|Episodes 1\u201312<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biz.heraldcorp.com/culture/view.php?ud=201907011219068918620_1|title=\uc774\uaddc\ud55c, \"'\uc11c\uc6b8\uba54\uc774\ud2b83' \uba54\uc774\ud2b8, \ub3c4\ubcbd\ub9cc \uc5c6\uae38 \ubc14\ub780\ub2e4\"|last=\ud5e4\ub7f4\ub4dc\uacbd\uc81c|date=2019-07-01|website=biz.heraldcorp.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Hosting ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!Year\n!Title\n!Network\n!Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2015 \n| ''[[K-pop Star 4]]''\n|SBS \n| with [[Jun Hyun-moo]]\n|-\n| ''Super Idol!''\n| [[MBC Music]] & TV Zone\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2|2016\n|''5th [[Gaon Chart K-Pop Awards]]''\n|[[KBS N|KBS Joy]] \n|with [[Leeteuk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201601251433187536766_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Yura, Leeteuk to host Gaon Chart K-pop Awards|date=January 25, 2016|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> \n|-\n| ''Tasty Road'' \n| [[O'live]]\n| with [[Kim Min-jung (actress)|Kim Min-jung]]\n|- \n|rowspan=3|2017\n|''[[Life Bar|Life Bar Season 2]]''\n| tvN \n| with [[Shin Dong-yup (comedian)|Shin Dong-yup]], [[Kim Jun-hyun (comedian)|Kim Jun-hyun]], and [[Kim Hee-chul]]\n|-\n|''Beauty Bible 2017''\n| KBS \n|with [[Han Jin|Han Hye-jin]] and [[Im Soo-hyang]] \n|-\n|''[[Battle Trip]]''\n|KBS2\n|(Special MC)\nEpisode 54\u201357<ref>{{cite web|title='Battle' Girl's Day Yura is Special MC for 4 weeks! [Battle Trip]|url=http://kbsworld.kbs.co.kr/news/news_view.php?no=17148|website=KBS World|accessdate=|date=June 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\u20132019\n|Weekly China Now \n|ZHTV\n|With Kim Il-Jung \n|- \n|2018\n|''2018 Miss Korea Pageant ''\n| MBC Every1\n|With [[Park Soo-hong]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3049685&cloc=joongangdaily|title=Girl's Day's Yura will host 2018 Miss Korea|date=June 23, 2018|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n|- \n|2018\n|''[[Idol Star Athletics Championships]]''\n| MBC\n|Chuseok Special (Bowling) With [[Boom (entertainer)]]\n|- \n|2019\n|''[[Idol Star Athletics Championships]]''\n| MBC\n|New Year Special (Bowling) With [[Kim Shin-young]]  and [[Shindong]]\n|}\n\n===Music video appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song title\n! Artist\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2014 || \"Night & Day\" || [[Wheesung]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.soompi.com/article/607715wpp/wheesungs-mv-teaser-for-night-and-day-features-girls-days-yura-and-teen-tops-c-a-p}}</ref>\n|-\n\n| 2015 || \"On Rainy Days\u201d || [[Kim Tae Bum (Party Street)]] feat [[Sojin]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.koreaboo.com/article/kim-tae-bum-reveals-mv-teaser-rainy-days-ft-girls-day-sojin/}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Girl's Day}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Work             \n! Result\n|-\n| 2014   \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[MBC Entertainment Awards]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Rookie Female Award<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Ji-yeon|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c&\ud61c\ub9ac, \uc5ec\uc790 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1 \"\uac00\uc218\uac00 \ubc1b\uc544\ub3c4 \ub418\ub294 \uc9c0\u2026\" (2014 MBC \ubc29\uc1a1\uc5f0\uc608\ub300\uc0c1)|trans-title=Girl's Day Yura & Hyeri Won Rookie of The Year|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=1419855979826085019|website=TV Daily|accessdate=2015-01-01|date=December 29, 2014|language=ko}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''[[We Got Married (Season 4)|We Got Married]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2015\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2015 Cable TV Broadcast Awards\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Popularity Award<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Seon-hwa|title='\ucf00\uc774\ube14TV \uc2dc\uc0c1\uc2dd' \uc720\ub77c, \"'\ub3c4\ub3c4\ud558\ub77c' \ucc0d\uc73c\uba74\uc11c \uc815\ub9d0 \ud589\ubcf5\ud588\ub2e4\"|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=671560/|website=TV Report|accessdate=2015-03-15|date=March 13, 2015|language=ko}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Dodohara''\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n*{{IMDb person|id=7184633}}\n*{{HanCinema person}}\n\n{{Girl's Day}}\n{{K-pop Star}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yura}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean female idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean female pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Ulsan]]\n[[Category:South Korean television personalities]]\n[[Category:South Korean dance musicians]]\n[[Category:South Korean television actresses]]\n[[Category:Girl's Day members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean singer}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Yura\n| image           = Yura - 2016 Gaon Chart K-pop Awards red carpet 03.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| caption         = Yura on the red carpet of the Gaon Chart K-pop Awards, on February 17, 2016.\n| native_name     = \uae40\uc544\uc601\n| birth_name      = Kim Ah-young\n| alias           = Yura\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1992|11|6}}\n| birth_place     = [[Ulsan]], South Korea\n| education       = [[Dongduk Women's University]]\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|actress}}\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = [[K-pop]]\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| years_active    = 2010\u2013present\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dream T Entertainment|Dream T]]|Awesome Ent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3061203|title=Girl's Day members pivot to acting|date=March 30, 2019|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>}}\n| associated_acts = [[Girl's Day]]\n}}}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = {{linktext|\uae40|\uc544\uc601}}\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u4e9e|\u7469}}\n| rr              = Gim A-yeong\n| mr              = Kim Ay\u014fng\n| hangulstage     = {{linktext|\uc720|\ub77c}}\n| hanjastage      = {{linktext|\u5ba5|\u62c9}}\n| rrstage         = Yu-ra\n| mrstage         = Yura\n}}\n\n'''Kim Ah-young''' (born November 6, 1992),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%9C%A0%EB%9D%BC&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=189556|title=\uc720\ub77c \ud504\ub85c\ud544|work=Naver|language=ko}}</ref> better known by her stage name '''Yura''', is a South Korean singer and actress. She is best known as a member of the South Korean [[girl group]] [[Girl's Day]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nYura was born on November 6, 1992 in [[Ulsan]], South Korea.<ref name=mk /> She attended Ulsan Art High School as a dance major. Yura is currently attending [[Dongduk Women's University]], alongside fellow group member [[Bang Min-ah|Minah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2011&no=75199|title= \uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, \ub3d9\ub355\uc5ec\ub300 \ubc29\uc1a1\uc5f0\uc608\uacfc \uc9c4\ud559 '2011\ub144 \uc0c8\ub0b4\uae30 |work=MK News|date=February 5, 2011|language=ko}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===2010: Girl's Day===\nIn 2010, Yura became a member of the K-pop girl group [[Girl's Day]], where she and [[Lee Hye-ri]] replaced two of the former members, Ji-in and Ji-sun, who left after having been with the group for two months.<ref name=mk>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/40220|title=[Interview] My Name Is\u2026 Girl's Day \u2013 Part. 1|date=December 9, 2012|work=TenAsia}}</ref> Dream Tea promoted Girl's Day before their debut with the creation of an official Fan Caf\u00e9, a YouTube channel, and Twitter accounts for the group and each of its members. The group also conducted a flash mob dance before the debut in the commercial and entertainment districts of [[Seoul]], gaining much interest.\n\n===2012\u20132014: Acting debut and collaborations===\nIn 2012, Yura made her acting debut through [[Sohu|Sohu TV]]'s Chinese drama ''Secret Angel''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/10159|title=Girl's Day Yura joins Jang Woo-hyuk in Chinese drama \"Secret Angel\"|date=March 7, 2012|work=TenAsia}}</ref> She then collaborated with her label-mate Jevice with their single \"I'll Love You\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} Yura also featured in [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]'s series ''[[To the Beautiful You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2012080910312231627&type=3|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\uc544\uadf8\ub300' \uce90\uc2a4\ud305..\uc774\ubbfc\ud638 \uc5f4\ud608\ud32c \uc5ed|date=August 9, 2012|work=Star News|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Yura was cast in the sitcom ''Reckless Family 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/66199|title=Girl's Day Yura Cast in Sitcom|date=July 24, 2013|work=10Asia}}</ref> She also featured in a special episode of KBS' night show ''The Clinic for Married Couples: Love and War 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/68096|title=ZE:A Moon Jun-young to Pair Up with Girl's Day Yura in TV Show|date=August 7, 2013|work=TenAsia}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, Yura starred in the SBS mini drama ''Be Arrogant''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/news_detail.asp?mediaCodeNo=258&newsId=01243126606255216|title='\ub3c4\ub3c4\ud558\ub77c' \uc720\ub77c\u00b7\uc2e0\uc18c\uc728, '2014 \ub2e8\ub9c9\uadf9 \ud398\uc2a4\ud2f0\ubc8c' \ud3ec\ubb38 \uc5f0\ub2e4|date=October 21, 2014|work=E Daily|language=ko}}</ref> She then became one of the official couples for the variety show ''[[We Got Married]]'', where she was paired with model-actor [[Hong Jong-hyun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.asiatoday.co.kr/view.php?key=20140529001128565|title=Model-actor Hong Jong-hyun and Girl's Day Yura join 'We Got Married'|date=May 29, 2014|work=Asia Today}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: MC and acting===\nIn 2015, Yura co-hosted the [[K-pop Star 4|fourth season]] of reality competition series ''[[K-pop Star]]'' alongside [[Jun Hyun-moo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003015182|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, 'K\ud31d\uc2a4\ud0c04' \uc0dd\ubc29\uc1a1 MC \ud569\ub958..\uc804\ud604\ubb34\uc640 \ud638\ud761|date=March 12, 2015|work=Osen|language=ko}}</ref> Additionally, Yura also serves as the MC for joint Korean-Chinese audition program ''Super Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000493065|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\uc288\ud37c\uc544\uc774\ub3cc' MC \ub099\uc810\u2026\uc870\ub825\uc790 \uc5ed\ud560|date=July 9, 2015|work=Xports News|language=ko}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2016, Yura was cast as one of the new MCs of Olive Channel's ''Tasty Road'' with [[Kim Min-jung (actress)|Kim Min-jung]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1110336196|title=\uae40\ubbfc\uc815\u00b7\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ud14c\uc774\uc2a4\ud2f0 \ub85c\ub4dc' MC \ud655\uc815|date=January 19, 2016|work=Osen|language=ko}}</ref> The same year, she joined tvN's variety show ''After the Play Ends'' and acted in the web drama ''Iron Lady''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=14672438801131175019|title='\uc5f0\uadf9\uc774 \ub05d\ub098\uace0 \ub09c \ub4a4' \ud558\uc11d\uc9c4\u00b7\uc724\uc18c\ud76c\u00b7\uc774\ubbfc\ud601\u00b7\uc720\ub77c, \uc0dd\uc0dd\ud55c \ud604\uc7a5\ucef7|date=June 30, 2016|work=TV Daily|language=ko}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Yura was cast as one of the new MCs of [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]'s ''Life Bar'' with [[Kim Hee-chul]], joining original MCs [[Shin Dong-yup (comedian)|Shin Dong-yup]] and [[Kim Jun-hyun (comedian)|Kim Jun-hyun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201704191651001775141_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Super Junior's Kim Hee-chul, Girl's Day's Yura to host 'Life Bar'|date=April 19, 2017|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> She was also chosen as one of the MCs for KBS Drama's ''Beauty Bible 2017'', alongside [[Han Hye-jin]]  and [[Im Soo-hyang]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0002908809|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ubdf0\ud2f0 \ubc14\uc774\ube14 2017' MC \ubc1c\ud0c1..\u65b0 \ubdf0\ud2f0\uc5ec\uc2e0|work=Herald Corporation|language=ko|date=April 6, 2017|accessdate=2017-06-12}}</ref> The same year, she starred in JTBC's short drama ''Hip Hop Teacher''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=117&aid=0002901082|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] \uc218\uc601\u00b7\uc774\uc6d0\uadfc\ubd80\ud130 \uc720\ub77c\u00b7\ub2c9\ucfe4\uae4c\uc9c0\u2026JTBC, \uc6f9\ub4dc \ub77c\uc778\uc5c5 \uacf5\uac1c|work=My Daily|language=ko|date=April 20, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Yura starred in KBS' romance drama ''[[Radio Romance (TV series)|Radio Romance]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kbsworld.kbs.co.kr/news/news_view.php?no=18016|title=Girl's Day Yura to star in 'Radio Romance' with Kim So Hyun & Yoon Doo Joon|website=KBS World|publisher=KBS World|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201804011415228184249_2|title=Yura in love with sweet villain character|date=April 1, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Lawsuit===\nOn November 8, 2010, Yura's ex-management company Action Music Entertainment filed an injunction against Yura, stopping her from signing a second contract with Dream Tea Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/11/08/2010110801660.html|title='\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774' \uc720\ub77c, \uc5f0\uc608\ud65c\ub3d9 \uae08\uc9c0 \uac00\ucc98\ubd84 \uc18c\uc1a1 \ub2f9\ud574|date=November 8, 2010|work=Chosun|language=ko}}</ref> In response, representatives of Dream Tea stated Action Music had violated contractual terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010110813305072713|title='\uc18c\uc1a1' \uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uce21 \"\uc720\ub77c, \uc544\ubb34 \ubb38\uc81c \uc5c6\uc774 \uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \uc774\uc801\"|date=November 11, 2010|work=Asiae|language=ko}}</ref> The lawsuit was pursued when Action Music insisted that they had a video of Yura's unacceptable behavior. On January 20, 2011, the court ruled in Yura's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.segye.com/newsView/20110128001761|title='\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774' \uc720\ub77c, \u524d\uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \ubd84\uc7c1\uc5d0\uc11c \uc774\uacbc\ub2e4|work=Segye|date=January 28, 2011|language=ko}}</ref> \n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Girl's Day discography}}\n\n===As featured artist===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Title\n! rowspan=2 | Year\n! colspan=\"1\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=2 | Sales\n! rowspan=2 | Album\n|-\n! style=\"font-size:90%;\"| [[Gaon Digital Chart|KOR<br>Gaon]]\n|-\n| \"I'll Love You\" <br>{{small|(Jevice featuring Yura of [[Girl's Day]])}}<br> || 2012 || \u2014 || \u2014 || {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010 || ''I Trusted Him'' || || [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] || Cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2012 || ''The Secret Angel'' || Yu-bin || [[Sohu|Sohu TV]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[To the Beautiful You]]'' || Lee Eun-young || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n| ''Reckless Family 3'' || Park Yoo-ra || [[MBC Every 1]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Family (2012 TV series)|Family]]'' ||  || rowspan=2|[[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS2]] || Cameo, Episode 11<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kwon|first1=Hye-rim|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c, '\ubb34\uc791\uc815\ud328\ubc00\ub9ac3' \uce90\uc2a4\ud305|trans-title=Girl's Day Yura Cast in 'Recklessly family 3'|url=http://joynews.inews24.com/php/news_view.php?g_menu=700200&g_serial=759665&rrf=nv|website=Joy News|accessdate=2013-08-03|date=July 17, 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n| ''The Clinic for Married Couples: Love and War 2'' || Yoo-jung |