[GamePro]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050206185354/http://gamepro.com/microsoft/xbox/games/reviews/27873.shtml |archivedate=2005-02-06 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| GameRev = B\u2212<ref>{{cite web |last=Liu |first=Johnny |date=February 2003 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/doa-xtreme-beach-volleyball |title=DOA Xtreme Beach Volleyball Review |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=2003-01-22 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/dead-or-alive-xtreme-beach-volleyball-review/1900-2909414/ |title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Padilla |first=Raymond |date=2003-01-26 |url=http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/dead-or-alive-xtreme-beach-volleyball/5556p1.html |title=GameSpy: Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| GameZone = 9.2/10<ref name=GameZone/>\n| IGN = 9.2/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Boulding |first=Aaron |date=2003-01-22 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/01/22/dead-or-alive-xtreme-beach-volleyball-review |title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| OXM = 8.4/10<ref>{{cite journal |title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball |magazine=[[Official Xbox Magazine]] |date=March 2003 |page=72}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev1Score = B<ref name=EW>{{cite journal |last=Walk |first=Gary Eng |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2003/02/07/dead-or-alive-xtreme-beach-volleyball |title=DEAD OR ALIVE XTREME BEACH VOLLEYBALL Review |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=694 |date=2003-02-07 |page=90 |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Playboy]]''\n| rev2Score = 74%<ref name=Playboy>{{cite journal |url=http://www.playboy.com/arts-entertainment/games/xtremebeachvolleyball/index.html |title=Dead or Alive: Xtreme Beach Volleyball |magazine=[[Playboy]] |year=2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040222014704/http://www.playboy.com/arts-entertainment/games/xtremebeachvolleyball/index.html |archivedate=2004-02-22 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2014-10-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nReviewers were mostly positive, especially to the depth of the volleyball game, as well as with the high quality of the visuals and animation.<ref name=GameZone>{{cite web | url=http://xbox.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20536.htm | title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball Review | last=Valentino | first=Nick | publisher=GameZone | date=2003-02-03 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006122131/http://xbox.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20536.htm | archivedate=2008-10-06 | url-status=dead | accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref> Review scores ranged from poor to very high, resulting in the averaged ratings of 74% at [[GameRankings]]<ref name=\"GR\" /> and 73/100 at [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" />\n\nIn its review, ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' focused on the game's unusual social, rather than adversarial, focus.<ref name=Edge>{{cite journal|author=Edge staff |title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |issue=121 |date=March 2003 |page=86}}</ref> ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' gave the game a score of eight out of ten and stated that \"The sharp graphics and advanced [[Breast physics|jiggle physics]] will no doubt prick the interest of lonely gamers, but surprisingly, the game's volleyball action is pretty solid. And that's the most important thing... right?\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Porter |first=Alex |date=2003-01-22 |url=http://www.maximonline.com/entertainment/reviews/review_games_4654.html |title=Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball |magazine=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030122141518/http://www.maximonline.com/entertainment/reviews/review_games_4654.html |archivedate=2003-01-22 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a B and said, \"It's kinda difficult not to get caught up in this goofy title, as you use your v-ball winnings to buy shoes and skimpy clothes for your fellow beach bunnies.\"<ref name=EW/> ''[[Playboy]]'' gave it a score of 74% and said, \"As long as you know what you're in for, ''DOA: Xtreme Beach Volleyball'' can be a mildly entertaining collection of digital diversions with, at the very least, the best-looking virtual women to grace a video game.\"<ref name=Playboy/>\n\nAt the first [[VGX (award show)|Spike Video Game Awards]] in 2003, ''Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball '' won in the category Best Animation.<ref>\"Spike TV honors digital women, Ray Liotta in video game awards\", ''The Victoria Advocate'', December 4, 2003.</ref> In 2006, [[GamesRadar]] ranked [[gravure idol|gravure]] scenes in the game to be one of the 100 greatest gaming moment in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/101-greatest-gaming-moments-day-one/?page=10 |title=101 Greatest Gaming Moments, Day One (Page 10) |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |date=2006-11-07 |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nShortly after the game's launch, a community of hobbyist hackers reverse engineered ''Dead or Alive Extreme Volleyball''\u2019s texture system, allowing users to modify textures of the player character models. This quickly led to users replacing the already revealing swimsuits with high detailed nude textures include genitalia and pubic hair for all in game characters. This resulted in fully nude female characters that would lounge about and play volleyball with full breast and buttocks physics intact. In January 2005, ninjahacker.net was taken to court by Tecmo for breaching the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] by [[reverse engineering]] aspects of the game, as well as ''[[Ninja Gaiden (2004 video game)|Ninja Gaiden]]'' and ''[[Dead or Alive 2]]''. The company was seeking between $1,000 and $10,000 for every skin swapped over the community website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/the-most-offensive-video-games-to-women/4/ |title=The most offensive video games to women |publisher=CBS News |date=2017-08-17 |accessdate=2017-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/02/10/tecmo_sues_xbox_game_hackers/ |title=Tecmo Sues Xbox Game Hackers |website=[[The Register]] |date=2005-03-10 |accessdate=2012-11-12}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100227100434/http://www.tecmo.co.jp/teamninja/product_bv.htm Official website]\n*{{MobyGames|id=/xbox/dead-or-alive-xtreme-beach-volleyball}}\n\n{{Dead or Alive series}}\n{{Team Ninja|state=collapsed}}\n{{Tomonobu Itagaki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dead Or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball}}\n[[Category:2003 video games]]\n[[Category:Beach volleyball video games]]\n[[Category:Dead or Alive (franchise) video games]]\n[[Category:Koei Tecmo franchises]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Photography simulation games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games with custom soundtrack support]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Xbox-only games]]\n[[Category:Bish\u014djo games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball\n| image = doaxbvbox.jpg\n| developer = [[Team Ninja]]\n| publisher = [[Tecmo]]\n| producer = [[Tomonobu Itagaki]]<br>Mitsuo Osada\n| designer = Tomonobu Itagaki<br>Katsunori Ehara<br>Motohiro Shiga\n| programmer = Takeshi Sawatari\n| series = ''[[Dead or Alive (series)|Dead or Alive]]''\n| platforms = [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n| released = {{Video game release|NA|January 22, 2003|JP|January 23, 2003|EU|March 28, 2003}}\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''''Dead or Alive Xtreme Beach Volleyball'''''|\u30c7\u30c3\u30c9\u30aa\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30a8\u30af\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u30d3\u30fc\u30c1\u30d0\u30ec\u30fc\u30dc\u30fc\u30eb|Deddo Oa Araibu Ekusutor\u012bmu B\u012bchi Bar\u0113b\u014dru|extra=abbreviated as '''''DOAX'''''|lead=yes}} is a [[beach volleyball]] [[Video game|game]] by [[Tecmo]] released in 2003 exclusively for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]. The game was a departure from the rest of the ''[[Dead or Alive (series)|Dead or Alive]]'' series which otherwise consisted of [[fighting game]]s. It also marked the first game in the series to have a Mature rating from the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]].\n\nThe game is set immediately after the tournament in ''[[Dead or Alive 3]]'' ended. Gameplay revolves around the women of the ''DOA'' series playing various mini-games in the many locations of Zack Island, a reclusive private resort on an island owned by [[Zack (Dead or Alive)|Zack]], the only male character from the series to appear anywhere in the game. This installment features no fighting engine, instead being much like a simulation game that encourages the player to establish relationships with the [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] of characters, and eventually make a two-person team to compete in volleyball competitions. Currency earned from completing mini-games and gambling in the island's casino allow the player to purchase hundreds of different swimsuits to wear in the game.\n\nIts sequel, ''[[Dead or Alive Xtreme 2]]'', was released on November 13, 2006, exclusively for the [[Xbox 360]]. The next sequel, ''[[Dead or Alive Xtreme 3]]'', was released on March 24, 2016 in Asian countries exclusively for  [[Sony]]'s [[video game console]]s, [[PlayStation 4]] and [[PlayStation Vita]].\n\n== Gameplay ==\nIn the main story mode, players select a woman to play as for the duration of their two-week period. Since the [[volleyball]] matches in the game are always two on two, the player automatically begins with a partner. Each day, players can select one activity in the morning, one in the afternoon, and one in the evening. While players do have an opportunity to simply relax during these time periods, they are generally used to either court new partners, or to challenge existing partnerships to a game of volleyball. Winning a match provides money which can be used to buy swimsuits and accessories, either for oneself, or as gifts to bestow upon the other women. Alternatively, players can also earn money through [[gambling]] at a casino located on the island.\n\nPlaying volleyball is done primarily through the use of two buttons, one designated for [[volleyball jargon|spiking]] and blocking, and the other for receiving or setting. As many of the actions happen automatically (e.g., jumping up to spike the ball), the game forces the player to focus on timing; a poorly timed press of a button results in a weak hit or a smash into the net. While it is possible to manually direct one's partner towards or away from the net, she will generally move to cover whichever area the player has left empty. The game is one of the few to make use of the analog sensitivity of the face buttons on the Xbox controller, with a softer touch allowing one to barely hit the ball over the net.\n\nIn addition to the core volleyball mechanic, the game features a relationship system between the various women on the island. Through gifts and skillful play, players can induce other characters to increase their esteem and positive feelings toward the character being played. A positive relationship with one's partner can translate into better performance during a volleyball match, while strong relationships with the other women leads to opportunities for new partners. Conversely, negative feelings from a partner can lead to missteps on the court, or can lead to gifts being thrown away unopened.\n\nAll money carries over between vacations, so that unspent \"Zack bucks\" can be used by a different character selected on the next play-through. Similarly, all swimsuits acquired by a given character remain with that character for all future play sessions. Since each character has access to a different set of swimsuits at the shop, the majority of suits for each character can only be acquired as gifts. Many of the costumes are very revealing and make the women appear almost nude in some instances. This, coupled with the suggestive poses the women present themselves in (which can be viewed and zoomed in on from almost any angle, as controlled by the player) led to the first Mature rating in the series' history.\n\n== Characters ==\nThe playable characters consist of seven females from the previous ''Dead or Alive'' titles, plus Lisa, who makes her first appearance in this title. [[Zack (Dead or Alive)|Zack]] (voiced by [[Dennis Rodman]]) is not a playable character but appears in the game's beginning and ending cinematics, with small appearances throughout the game. His girlfriend, [[Nikki (Dead or Alive character)|Niki]], appears only in cutscenes. As such, the volleyball players consist of:\n\n* [[Ayane (Dead or Alive)|Ayane]] \u2013 Japanese ninja and rival (as well as half-sister) of Kasumi.\n* [[Christie (Dead or Alive)|Christie]] \u2013 British assassin and automobile enthusiast.\n* [[Helena Douglas|Helena]] \u2013 French opera singer fond of walking her dog.\n* [[Hitomi (Dead or Alive)|Hitomi]] \u2013 German/Japanese high-school student and aspiring chef.\n* [[Kasumi (Dead or Alive)|Kasumi]] \u2013 Japanese runaway ninja who enjoys fortune-telling and [[origami]].\n* [[Leifang]] \u2013 Chinese college student with an interest in [[aromatherapy]].\n* [[List of Dead or Alive characters#La Mariposa/Lisa Hamilton|Lisa]] \u2013 American stock broker and amateur surfer.\n* [[Tina Armstrong|Tina]] \u2013 American wrestler and daughter of [[Bass Armstrong]].\n\nEach of the playable characters has her own likes and dislikes (documented in the game manual), which influence how likely she is to accept or be impressed by certain gifts. Favorable gifts include those based on her favorite food, favorite color, and hobbies. In order to suit the lighter, more playful nature of the game, the ''Dead or Alive'' characters' previous rivalries were reduced to just a general dislike in this title. As a result, even characters who would normally try to kill another (such as Ayane and Kasumi, or Christie and Helena) can become fast friends through a brief exchange of gifts.\n\n==Plot==\nZack gambles his winnings from the ''[[Dead or Alive 3]]'' tournament at a casino. In the process, he hits the jackpot, earning a ridiculously large sum of money. The money is used to purchase a private island, which he promptly turns into a resort named after himself (\"Zack Island\"). He then invites the women from the previous tournament (along with one newcomer &mdash; his girlfriend, Niki) to his island under the pretense that the next Dead or Alive tournament will be held there. The women arrive and after discovering the truth, (namely that it was merely a hoax) decide to make the best of the situation by spending two weeks vacationing on the island.\n\nAt the end of the two-week time period, the ladies depart, leaving only Zack and Niki on the island. Shortly thereafter, a volcano, previously thought to be inactive, spontaneously erupts, threatening to destroy Zack's island. In the chaos, Niki escapes using Zack's jetpack. Zack survives the volcanic eruption, but the island itself is completely destroyed. While not part of the game itself, Zack's later ''[[Dead or Alive 4]]'' ending shows the pair robbing an ancient tomb and escaping with a truck filled with gold, suggesting a possible financing source for a sequel. In the sequel, it is confirmed that this is indeed the source for financing \"New Zack Island\".\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 5px;\"\n|-\n! Song title\n! Artist\n|- style\n|\"[[Is Th